   =20
      Banque Havilland
   =20
 =20
When I worked as an investment banker I kept a folder in my desk in which I=
 saved particularly bad pitchbook pages; perhaps my greatest regret from ba=
nking is that I=C2=A0did not sneak this folder out when I quit. I promise i=
t was good. So I consider myself a bit of a connoisseur of bad banking pitc=
hes. But probably the worst I have ever seen was a pitch by Banque Havillan=
d SA=C2=A0to a United Arab Emirates sovereign wealth fund that was reported=
 in the Intercept in 2017. The pitch was not for a promising=C2=A0investmen=
t opportunity but rather =E2=80=9Ca plan for the United Arab Emirates to wa=
ge financial war against its Gulf rival Qatar=E2=80=9D by driving down its =
bond prices or something. =E2=80=9CControl the yield curve, decide the futu=
re,=E2=80=9D was the tag line, and then there was some pretty high-level di=
scussion of, like, you buy credit default swaps on Qatar, you do some wash =
trading =E2=80=A6=C2=A0honestly in addition to being a pitch for economic w=
arfare and market manipulation, it did not make a ton of sense on its own t=
erms? Basically you buy a lot of Qatari CDS and then you rub your hands tog=
ether and cackle I guess. Anyway:Banque Havilland SA, the Luxembourg-based =
lender that counts Prince Andrew as one of its clients, was issued with a w=
arning notice by the U.K. financial regulator over its alleged role in an e=
conomic boycott of Qatar.Controlled by financier and U.K. Conservative Part=
y backer David Rowland, the lender gave =E2=80=9Cimproper advice=E2=80=9D i=
n a presentation that set out =E2=80=9Cmanipulative trading practices=E2=80=
=9D over Qatari bonds, the Financial Conduct Authority said Tuesday. The pr=
esentation could be taken to harm the Qatari economy, it said.A spokesperso=
n for Banque Havilland said no findings had yet been made by the regulator =
and it was challenging the warning notice through the FCA=E2=80=99s interna=
l processes. The warning =E2=80=9Crefers to historic allegations of miscond=
uct at the bank=E2=80=99s London premises in 2017.=E2=80=9DHere is the (ver=
y brief) warning notice. The presentation definitely called for manipulativ=
e trading practices! =E2=80=9CIncrease long CDS positions slowly with large=
 banks, just enough to move the price sufficiently to make it newsworthy,=
=E2=80=9D it said. =E2=80=9CEstablish a crossing transaction arrangement wh=
ereby another affiliated party sells the same bond holdings back to the ori=
ginal seller and thereby creates additional downward pressure,=E2=80=9D it =
said. It is all a bit zany, and=C2=A0hard to believe it was written by a pr=
ofessional banker or trader. But if you are a bank and you write a pitch de=
ck about how one country can manipulate markets to harm another country=E2=
=80=99s economy I guess you really should expect to get a warning from the =
FCA.
