<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The Fed vs. stablecoins</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most obvious risk of stablecoins i=
s that they won=E2=80=99t be stable. Stablecoins are crypto tokens that are=
 pegged to the dollar (or to some other fiat currency or non-crypto thing).=
 All of the popular ways to create stablecoins involve some risk that the p=
eg will fail and the stablecoin won=E2=80=99t be worth a dollar. The simple=
st approach =E2=80=94=C2=A0issue one stablecoin for one dollar, invest the =
dollar in safe-ish cash-like assets, and promise to redeem the stablecoins =
for dollars =E2=80=94=C2=A0runs the risk that the issuer will invest its do=
llars in not-quite-safe assets that lose value, or will just steal the doll=
ars, and when stablecoin holders ask for their money back it won=E2=80=99t =
be there. This also creates risks of runs (people will ask for their dollar=
s back preemptively) and contagion (when they ask for their dollars back, t=
he stablecoin issuer will have to sell its assets rapidly, driving down the=
 price of those assets and causing losses in the regular financial system).=
 Other approaches to stablecoins =E2=80=94=C2=A0overcollateralizing them wi=
th volatile crypto assets, using some algorithmic stabilization mechanism=
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0can also break if, basically, the prices of other cryp=
to tokens go down. These risks are quite salient =E2=80=94=C2=A0algorithmic=
 stablecoins <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26561=
